Step 1 : Load and Prepare the data

# Define the file path to CSV in the Downloads folder
file_path <- "~/Downloads/Merged_Traffic_and_Store_Data_with_Coordinates.csv"

# Load the dataset
traffic_data <- read.csv(file_path)

# Display the first few rows to confirm successful loading
head(traffic_data)

FYI :

Estimated_Traffic: Represents the predicted number of customers expected to visit a store and quantitative measure of the demand a store might experience, derived from factors like attractiveness, accessibility, and customer behavior. Tells us how many customers are likely to visit this store
Mean_Utility: Reflects the calculated attractiveness of a store based on socio-demographic characteristics, which is a qualitative measure of how well a store matches the demographic profile of its surrounding population (income, education, population density). It tell us how well this store aligns with the preferences and demographics of the target population

Step 4 : Fit a Global regression Model (Baseline)

Before running GWR, we fit a global regression model to understand the overall relationship between the independent variables and Estimated_Traffic.

# Fit a global regression model

Step 6 : Analyze and Visualize GWR results

1 . Local Coefficients

# Extract local coefficients and convert to a data frame
local_coefficients <- as.data.frame(gwr_model$SDF)

# Plot local coefficients for Mean Utility
ggplot(local_coefficients, aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude, color = Mean_Utility)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Local Coefficients for Mean Utility",
       x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", color = "Coefficient")

2. Local R Squared values

# Plot local R-squared values
ggplot(local_coefficients, aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude, color = Local_R2)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Local R-squared Values from GWR",
       x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", color = "R-squared")

Interpreting the Plot

High R-squared Areas (Yellow Regions):

These are locations where the GWR model performs well, meaning the predictors (e.g., Mean_Utility, Population_Density) explain most of the variation in Estimated_Traffic.

Low R-squared Areas (Purple Regions):

These are locations where the model doesnt fit as well. This could indicate: Missing predictors (e.g., proximity, competitive effects).

Spatial heterogeneity not captured by the included variables.

Geographic Insights: Notice clusters of high and low R-squared. This spatial clustering suggests areas where the relationship between predictors and traffic may differ, requiring further investigation.

3. With store names

# Add StoreID to the local coefficients data
local_coefficients$StoreID <- traffic_df$StoreID

# Plot R-squared by StoreID
ggplot(local_coefficients, aes(x = reorder(StoreID, Local_R2), y = Local_R2)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 3)) +
  labs(title = "Local R-squared Values by Store",
       x = "Store Name", y = "Local R-squared")

# Select top and bottom 10 stores by Local R-squared
top_bottom_stores <- local_coefficients %>%
  arrange(desc(Local_R2)) %>%
  slice(c(1:10, (n() - 9):n()))

# Plot
ggplot(top_bottom_stores, aes(x = reorder(StoreID, Local_R2), y = Local_R2)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Local R-squared Values (Top and Bottom Stores)",
       x = "Store Name", y = "Local R-squared")

From this bar chart of local R-squared values for the top and bottom stores, we can draw the following conclusions:

1. High Local R-squared Stores (e.g., H-E-B, Sams Club, Specs):

  • Interpretation: For these stores, the predictors in the GWR model (e.g., Mean_Utility, Population_Density, etc.) explain most of the variation in Estimated_Traffic. This means the model is highly effective at capturing the factors that drive customer traffic for these stores.
  • Actionable Insight: These stores may follow predictable patterns of traffic influenced by socio-demographic factors and store-specific attractiveness. The model can reliably be used for planning or analysis for such stores.

2. Low Local R-squared Stores (e.g., Hearing Aid Center, Kirklands):

  • Interpretation: For these stores, the model does not explain the variation in traffic well. This suggests:
    • Missing predictors (e.g., competition, accessibility, parking availability, or proximity to other points of interest).
    • Variability in traffic driven by non-modeled factors like niche customer preferences or unique store offerings.
  • Actionable Insight: Investigate additional variables or store-specific factors to improve the models performance in these cases.

3. General Trends:

  • Stores with higher traffic volumes or larger customer bases (e.g., H-E-B, Sams Club) tend to have higher R-squared values. This may indicate that traffic patterns for larger stores are more easily explained by socio-demographics and utility measures.
  • Smaller or niche stores (e.g., Hearing Aid Center) may require a more customized modeling approach to capture unique customer behaviors.

Next Steps for Improvement:

  1. Enhance the Model:
    • Add more predictors like proximity to competitors, parking availability, or store size.
    • Consider interactions between variables (e.g., Mean_Utility and Distance).
  2. Investigate Outliers:
    • Perform a qualitative review of stores with very low R-squared values to identify unmodeled factors.
  3. Use High R-squared Insights:
    • Stores with high R-squared values provide confidence that your model is robust in explaining traffic patterns for similar locations.

So far - we have done the following analysis:

Focus: The goal was to understand how well GWR explains customer traffic at different store locations.
Outputs:
Local R-squared values: Indicated the models explanatory power at each location.
Local coefficients: Explained how predictors (e.g., Mean_Utility) varied spatially.
Conclusion: It highlighted spatial heterogeneity in relationships and model fit but didnt directly predict traffic.

Fitting the GWR

library(sp)

# Ensure Latitude and Longitude columns are numeric
Final_data$Latitude <- as.numeric(Final_data$Latitude)
Final_data$Longitude <- as.numeric(Final_data$Longitude)

# Remove rows with missing Latitude or Longitude values (if any)
Final_data <- Final_data[!is.na(Final_data$Latitude) & !is.na(Final_data$Longitude), ]

# Convert Final_data to a SpatialPointsDataFrame
coordinates(Final_data) <- ~Longitude+Latitude  # Use Longitude and Latitude as coordinates
proj4string(Final_data) <- CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84")  # Assign WGS84 CRS

library(GWmodel)

# Select bandwidth
bw <- bw.gwr(Estimated_Traffic ~ Population + Education_Level + Median_Income + Population_Density,
             data = Final_data,
             adaptive = TRUE)
